[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Cervantes is a pleasant 81-year-old gentleman who is being seen at the request of Dr. Coll Surgical Service to discuss treatment recommendations following resection of a node-positive sigmoid colon cancer as well as a node-negative gallbladder adenocarcinoma.  Mr. Cervantes's history is as follows:
1.  September 21, 2010: Presented to local provider due to rectal bleeding.  He was at that time found to be anemic.  He was also experiencing chronic abdominal symptoms suggestive of symptomatic cholelithiasis with biliary colic, transient jaundice, abdominal pain, and dark urine.
2.  September 27, 2010: colonoscopy performed to the cecum noting that at 20 cm from the anal verge was a diffuse friable sigmoid colon apple core lesion, biopsy positive for infiltrating grade 2 (of 4) adenocarcinoma.  Also noted to have scattered diverticular disease.  CEA was noted to be elevated at 11.
3.  October 7, 2010: Presented to PCNH for further workup.  CT abdomen and pelvis noting a 4.4-cm lesion in the mid to distal sigmoid colon without evidence of adenopathy.  Also noted cholelithiasis with several small nodular thickening in the gallbladder wall, questioning polyps.  There was a 10 x 17 mm indeterminate region in the liver that was adjacent to the gallbladder fundus.
4.  October 12, 2010: Dr. Adams and Dr. Fredericks performed a low-anterior resection with mobilization of the splenic flexure, laparoscopic cholecystectomy.  Pathology from the tissue removed for the sigmoid, colon, and rectum notes an invasive grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma forming an ulcerating annular mass.  The tumor infiltrates through the muscularis propria to involve the pericolonic adipose tissue and the serosa in the region of perforation.  No definite angiolymphatic invasion identified.  Proximal distal resected margins negative.  Of 13 regional lymph nodes, two were positive for metastatic disease.  Pathology from the cholecystectomy is positive for invasive grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma forming a sessile polypoid mass involving the fundus.  The tumor infiltrates through the muscular layer to focally involve the perimuscular connective tissue.  Adenoma with high-grade dysplasia is present in the adjacent mucosa.  All resected margins are negative.  One pericystic duct lymph node-negative for tumor.
Sleepy.  On pain medications.  His family is present during this entire consultation.

